<body>
<segment id="1" parent="1001" relname="preparation">David Schonfeld</segment>
<segment id="2" parent="1003" relname="span">David Joseph Schonfeld</segment>
<segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration">( M.D. , FAAP )</segment>
<segment id="4" parent="1002" relname="same_unit">is a professor of the Practice in the Suzanne Dworak-Peck School of Social Work and Pediatrics at the University of Southern California and Children 's Hospital Los Angeles and director at the National Center for School Crisis and Bereavement .</segment>
<segment id="5" parent="1005" relname="preparation">Education</segment>
<segment id="6" parent="1007" relname="span">Schonfeld attended Boston University School of Medicine and Boston University College of Liberal Arts</segment>
<segment id="7" parent="1009" relname="span">from which he graduated with B.A.</segment>
<segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration">( Summa Cum Laude )</segment>
<segment id="9" parent="1011" relname="span">and M.D.</segment>
<segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration">( Magna Cum Laude )</segment>
<segment id="11" parent="1012" relname="span">along with Phi Beta Kappa and Pediatrics Award</segment>
<segment id="12" parent="1013" relname="span">-</segment>
<segment id="13" parent="12" relname="elaboration">all in 1983 .</segment>
<segment id="14" parent="1007" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="15" parent="1015" relname="span">Following graduation , he pursued residency in pediatrics at the Children 's Hospital of Philadelphia</segment>
<segment id="16" parent="15" relname="elaboration">at which he served until 1986 .</segment>
<segment id="17" parent="1017" relname="preparation">He quit the residency</segment>
<segment id="18" parent="1018" relname="preparation">following the advise of his mentor there ,</segment>
<segment id="19" parent="1018" relname="joint">who told him</segment>
<segment id="20" parent="1020" relname="span">that he should have pursued behavioral pediatrics fellowship</segment>
<segment id="21" parent="20" relname="circumstance">after Schonfeld complained to him</segment>
<segment id="22" parent="1022" relname="sequence">that he have learned how to take care of children 's illnesses ,</segment>
<segment id="23" parent="1025" relname="span">but he did n't go into pediatrics</segment>
<segment id="24" parent="23" relname="cause">because he loves illnesses .</segment>
<segment id="25" parent="1025" relname="evidence">[ 2 ]</segment>
<segment id="26" parent="1026" relname="span">He then pursued fellowship in behavioral and developmental pediatrics with the University of Maryland , Baltimore from which he graduated in 1989 .</segment>
<segment id="27" parent="26" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="28" parent="1028" relname="preparation">Career</segment>
<segment id="29" parent="1030" relname="preparation">1990s</segment>
<segment id="30" parent="1031" relname="span">Immediately after University of Maryland , David Schonfeld joined the faculty at Yale School of Medicine as an assistant professor of pediatrics , a position</segment>
<segment id="31" parent="30" relname="elaboration">which he kept until 1995 .</segment>
<segment id="32" parent="1034" relname="span">He then relocated to the Yale New Haven Hospital ,</segment>
<segment id="33" parent="1035" relname="joint">where he served as its director until 1998</segment>
<segment id="34" parent="1035" relname="joint">and from 1990 until 2005 maintained the same position at its Lead Program .</segment>
<segment id="35" parent="1034" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="36" parent="1038" relname="circumstance">When Gulf War broke out in 1991 ,</segment>
<segment id="37" parent="1038" relname="span">Schonfeld participated at a meeting</segment>
<segment id="38" parent="37" relname="elaboration">regarding children cope with war at the Yale Child Study Center , a department of the Yale School of Medicine .</segment>
<segment id="39" parent="1041" relname="span">There , he found out</segment>
<segment id="40" parent="1042" relname="span">that children at New Haven , Connecticut are more impacted by city violence then war .</segment>
<segment id="41" parent="40" relname="evidence">[ 2 ]</segment>
<segment id="42" parent="1044" relname="attribution">In an interview with Nicole Wise of The New York Times in 1992 , Dr. Schonfeld had suggested</segment>
<segment id="43" parent="1045" relname="joint">that parents should n't be afraid to talk to their children about AIDS</segment>
<segment id="44" parent="1046" relname="span">and should start explaining it to children</segment>
<segment id="45" parent="44" relname="elaboration">who are as early as 3-4 year old .</segment>
<segment id="46" parent="1045" relname="evidence">[ 3 ]</segment>
<segment id="47" parent="1030" relname="sequence">2000s</segment>
<segment id="48" parent="1030" relname="sequence">After September 11 attacks , he educated fellow teachers ' unions , such as the American Federation of Teachers , on how to help children to cope with a loss of their loved one .</segment>
<segment id="49" parent="1051" relname="span">In the study</segment>
<segment id="50" parent="49" relname="elaboration">that was conducted by him ,</segment>
<segment id="51" parent="1053" relname="attribution">it was revealed</segment>
<segment id="52" parent="1053" relname="joint">that only 7 % of teachers had received training</segment>
<segment id="53" parent="1054" relname="span">and only 3 % of school districts offer such courses .</segment>
<segment id="54" parent="53" relname="evidence">[ 2 ]</segment>
<segment id="55" parent="1056" relname="span">In 2005 , David Schonfeld had received funding from the September 11th Children 's Fund</segment>
<segment id="56" parent="1057" relname="joint">to establish National Center for School Crisis and Bereavement at the University of Southern California School of Social Work</segment>
<segment id="57" parent="1059" relname="span">and several years prior to it , he obtained additional funding from the New York Life Foundation</segment>
<segment id="58" parent="1060" relname="joint">to expand the center</segment>
<segment id="59" parent="1061" relname="span">and construct the Coalition</segment>
<segment id="60" parent="59" relname="purpose">to Support Grieving Students .</segment>
<segment id="61" parent="1059" relname="evidence">[ 2 ]</segment>
<segment id="62" parent="1063" relname="span">From 2005 to 2012 Schonfeld was the Thelma and Jack Rubinstein Professor of Pediatrics and director of the Division of Developmental and Behavioral Pediatrics</segment>
<segment id="63" parent="62" relname="evidence">[ 4 ] at Cincinnati Children 's Hospital Medical Center .</segment>
<segment id="64" parent="1030" relname="sequence">From 2006 to 2015 he was a visiting professor at the University of Eastern Piedmont and at the Vrije Universiteit Brussel .</segment>
<segment id="65" parent="1066" relname="preparation">2010s</segment>
<segment id="66" parent="67" relname="circumstance">When the shooting at Aurora , Colorado happened in 2012 ,</segment>
<segment id="67" parent="1068" relname="span">David Schonfeld was invited to speak at the school the next day .</segment>
<segment id="68" parent="1068" relname="evidence">[ 5 ]</segment>
<segment id="69" parent="1070" relname="span">From 2013 to 2015 he was pediatrician-in-chief at the St. Christopher 's Hospital for Children and chairman and professor of pediatrics at Drexel University College of Medicine .</segment>
<segment id="70" parent="69" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="71" parent="1072" relname="span">Upon expiration of his position at Drexel University , he joined the faculty of the University of Southern California and its Suzanne Dworak-Peck School of Social Work and Pediatrics .</segment>
<segment id="72" parent="71" relname="evidence">[ 2 ]</segment>
<segment id="73" parent="1074" relname="span">In 2015 he spoke on the Healthy Children Radio regarding natural disasters and gun violence and how to cope with them .</segment>
<segment id="74" parent="73" relname="evidence">[ 6 ]</segment>
<segment id="75" parent="1079" relname="span">In 2016 he , Steven Krug</segment>
<segment id="76" parent="75" relname="elaboration">( Northwestern University Feinberg School of Medicine )</segment>
<segment id="77" parent="1080" relname="span">and Daniel Fagbuyi</segment>
<segment id="78" parent="77" relname="elaboration">( George Washington University School of Medicine )</segment>
<segment id="79" parent="1081" relname="span">had compiled a report</segment>
<segment id="80" parent="79" relname="elaboration">in which they criticized the U.S. government for not providing enough funding for the medical needs of children during public health emergencies .</segment>
<segment id="81" parent="1077" relname="evidence">[ 7 ]</segment>
<segment id="82" parent="1084" relname="span">In March that year he spoke at a free community forum</segment>
<segment id="83" parent="1085" relname="span">to discuss childhood trauma and crisis of the Our Lady of the Lake Children 's Hospital</segment>
<segment id="84" parent="83" relname="elaboration">following the 2016 shooting of Baton Rouge police officers .</segment>
<segment id="85" parent="1084" relname="evidence">[ 8 ]</segment>
<segment id="86" parent="1088" relname="span">Following the 2017 Las Vegas shooting , David Schonfeld and Marleen Wong had traveled to Las Vegas</segment>
<segment id="87" parent="86" relname="elaboration">where they addressed issues on post-traumatic stress disorder , anxiety and grief .</segment>
<segment id="88" parent="1088" relname="evidence">[ 9 ]</segment>
<segment id="89" parent="1091" relname="span">In 2018 , Dr. Schonfeld and the New York Life Foundation had launched Grief-Sensitive Schools Initiative</segment>
<segment id="90" parent="1092" relname="span">which will train New York Life employees</segment>
<segment id="91" parent="90" relname="purpose">to deliver public speaking about grief in public schools .</segment>
<segment id="92" parent="1091" relname="evidence">[ 10 ]</segment>
<segment id="93" parent="1094" relname="circumstance">When Nipsey Hussle died in 2019 ,</segment>
<segment id="94" parent="1096" relname="span">Schonfeld was quoted by Fox News</segment>
<segment id="95" parent="94" relname="elaboration">saying ,</segment>
<segment id="96" parent="1097" relname="span">" People want to come together</segment>
<segment id="97" parent="96" relname="purpose">to support each other .</segment>
<segment id="98" parent="1099" relname="span">That 's really what makes us a community . "</segment>
<segment id="99" parent="98" relname="evidence">[ 11 ]</segment>
<segment id="100" parent="1094" relname="sequence">Positions</segment>
<segment id="101" parent="1102" relname="joint">From 1993 to 1994 Schonfeld served on the Nominations Committee of the Society for Developmental and Behavioral Pediatrics</segment>
<segment id="102" parent="1102" relname="joint">and from 1996 to 1999 was first chairman of the Research Committee at the same place .</segment>
<segment id="103" parent="1104" relname="joint">From 1997 to 2000 he served as the first SDBP Liaison to the AAP Committee on Pediatric Research</segment>
<segment id="104" parent="1104" relname="joint">and until 2002 was the first SDBP Liaison to the Alliance for Health and Behavior Research .</segment>
<segment id="105" parent="1105" relname="joint">From 1998 to 2002 Dr. Schonfeld served on the Executive Council</segment>
<segment id="106" parent="1105" relname="joint">and since 2000 he is a chair of the Trainee Manuscript Award Committee .</segment>
<segment id="107" parent="1107" relname="sequence">David Schonfeld also served on the Task Force on Terrorism from 2001 to 2004 and on the Committee on Resident Research Grants .</segment>
<segment id="108" parent="1109" relname="span">In addition , he is one of the initial members of the Subboard of Developmental Behavioral Pediatrics , as well as a member of the American Pediatric Society , Society for Pediatric Research , American Pediatric Association , and American School Health Association .</segment>
<segment id="109" parent="108" relname="evidence">[ 12 ]</segment>
<segment id="110" parent="1112" relname="span">In 2007 , David Schonfeld became President of the Society for Developmental and Behavioral Pediatrics .</segment>
<segment id="111" parent="110" relname="evidence">[ 13 ]</segment>
<segment id="112" parent="1113" relname="span">and in May of same year served on an Executive Council of the same place .</segment>
<segment id="113" parent="112" relname="evidence">[ 14 ]</segment>
<segment id="114" parent="1107" relname="sequence">From 2008 to 2010 he served on the Disaster Mental Health Subcommittee of the National Biodefense Science Board</segment>
<segment id="115" parent="1118" relname="span">Federal Advisory Committee under Homeland Security Presidential Directive 7</segment>
<segment id="116" parent="115" relname="elaboration">( formerly Presidential Policy Directive 21 )</segment>
<segment id="117" parent="1118" relname="evidence">[ 15 ]</segment>
<segment id="118" parent="1116" relname="same_unit">and Scientific and Program Committee of the International Pediatric Association .</segment>
<segment id="119" parent="1121" relname="span">He also served on the National Commission on Children and Disasters from 2008 to 2011</segment>
<segment id="120" parent="119" relname="evidence">[ 1 ]</segment>
<segment id="121" parent="1122" relname="span">and since 2009 serves as a member of the expert panel on the Child Development &amp; Behavior Branch .</segment>
<segment id="122" parent="121" relname="evidence">[ 16 ]</segment>
<segment id="123" parent="1126" relname="span">In 2013 , he was appointed to the Sandy Hook Advisory Commission by Dannel Malloy</segment>
<segment id="124" parent="123" relname="evidence">[ 17 ]</segment>
<segment id="125" parent="1127" relname="span">and in February that year became a chairman of the Department of Pediatrics at Drexel University College of Medicine .</segment>
<segment id="126" parent="125" relname="evidence">[ 4 ]</segment>
<segment id="127" parent="1130" relname="span">Since 2017 he serves as a benefactor at the Society for Developmental and Behavioral Pediatrics</segment>
<segment id="128" parent="127" relname="evidence">[ 18 ]</segment>
<segment id="129" parent="1131" relname="span">and as its pediatrician-in-chief .</segment>
<segment id="130" parent="129" relname="evidence">[ 19 ]</segment>
<segment id="131" parent="1132" relname="span">Since 2015 , David J. Schonfeld is on the American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology steering committee .</segment>
<segment id="132" parent="131" relname="evidence">[ 20 ]</segment>
<segment id="133" parent="1133" relname="span">Editorial work</segment>
<segment id="134" parent="1135" relname="span">Since 1996 ,</segment>
<segment id="135" parent="134" relname="evidence">[ 12 ]</segment>
<segment id="136" parent="1137" relname="span">David Schonfeld serves on an editorial board of the Journal of Developmental and Behavioral Pediatrics .</segment>
<segment id="137" parent="136" relname="evidence">[ 21 ]</segment>
<segment id="138" parent="1138" relname="span">He was a co-author with Thomas Demaria on book chapters such as " Child &amp; Disaster " and " Bereavement " .</segment>
<segment id="139" parent="138" relname="evidence">[ 22 ]</segment>
<segment id="140" parent="1140" relname="preparation">Personal life</segment>
<segment id="141" parent="1141" relname="span">Schonfeld have two grown up daughters</segment>
<segment id="142" parent="141" relname="evidence">[ 23 ]</segment>
<segment id="143" parent="1142" relname="span">one of which is Kim .</segment>
<segment id="144" parent="143" relname="evidence">[ 24 ]</segment>
